          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Stimulation of fatty acid oxidation </span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A 55-year-old man presents with fatigue, abdominal pain, and hepatomegaly, with abnormal liver function tests suggesting ethanol toxicity. What could be the underlying biochemical change associated with ethanol toxicity in this scenario?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q8661448",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30055,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. B) Increased NADH/NAD+ ratio&nbsp; </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Ethanol metabolism</strong> in the <strong>liver </strong>primarily involves <strong>alcohol dehydrogenase</strong> and <strong>aldehyde dehydrogenase</strong>, converting <strong>ethanol first</strong> to <strong>acetaldehyde</strong> and then to <strong>acetate,</strong> a process accompanied by the <strong>reduction of NAD+ to NADH.</strong> This <strong>shift towards an increased</strong> <strong>NADH/NAD+ ratio</strong> has<strong> several metabolic consequences</strong>, including<strong> inhibition of gluconeogenesis and fatty acid oxidation</strong>, and stimulation of<strong> lactate production </strong>(leading to an increased lactate/pyruvate ratio) and <strong>lipogenesis</strong>. The <strong>accumulation of NADH</strong> promotes the<strong> conversion of pyruvate to lactate and oxaloacetate to malate</strong>, contributing to<strong> lactic acidosis </strong>and<strong> malate accumulation,</strong> respectively. Furthermore, the <strong>increased NADH/NAD+ ratio </strong>disrupts the<strong> TCA cycle</strong> and encourages the <strong>synthesis of</strong> <strong>fatty acids, leading to fatty liver </strong>(<strong>steatosis</strong>), a common feature in <strong>chronic alcohol consumption.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">&nbsp;<u>Explanation:</u></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A. Decreased lactate/pyruvate ratio:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>Ethanol</strong> metabolism actually leads to an <strong>increased lactate/pyruvate ratio </strong>due to the conversion of<strong> pyruvate to lactate</strong> in the presence of excess <strong>NADH.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C. Stimulation of gluconeogenesis: Ethanol</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> metabolism <strong>inhibits gluconeogenesis</strong> due to the <strong>increased NADH/NAD+ ratio </strong>and the subsequent <strong>diversion </strong>of substrates like<strong> pyruvate and oxaloacetate</strong> to <strong>lactate and malate</strong>, respectively.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D. Stimulation of fatty acid oxidation:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>Ethanol </strong>metabolism <strong>inhibits fatty acid oxidation</strong>, again due to the <strong>increased</strong> <strong>NADH/NAD+ ratio.</strong> Instead, there is an <strong>accumulation of fatty acids</strong> leading to<strong> fatty liver.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Both the oxidation steps</strong> in <strong>alcohol metabolism produce NADH,</strong> resulting in a<strong> high NADH/NAD+ ratio.</strong> As a result, the following <strong>metabolic adaptations occur:</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"1\" style=\"list-style-type:lower-roman\">\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Lactic acidosis.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Hypoglycemia.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ketogenesis.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Fatty liver and steatosis.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Mitochondrial damage and apoptosis.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">CNS depression</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Lippincott 7/e:317, DM Vasudevan&nbsp; 9/e: p 140-141</span></strong></span></span></p>",
