        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. D)&nbsp; All the above</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Chronic alcoholism</strong> can lead to a range of<strong> biochemical and physiological changes</strong>, many of which are <strong>reflected in laboratory findings:</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A. Elevated GGT (Gamma-Glutamyl Transferase) activity:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>GGT</strong> is an enzyme involved in the <strong>metabolism of glutathione</strong> and is often <strong>elevated in alcohol-related liver disease</strong>. Its<strong> elevation</strong> is commonly used as a <strong>biomarker for excessive alcohol consumption </strong>and<strong> liver damage.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B. Elevated ALT (Alanine Aminotransferase) activity:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong> ALT</strong> is an enzyme<strong> found</strong> predominantly in the<strong> liver</strong>. Its<strong> elevation</strong> in the <strong>blood</strong> often indicates<strong> liver damage</strong>, which can occur as a result of <strong>chronic alcohol abuse.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C. Decreased ADH (Antidiuretic Hormone) activity:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong> Chronic alcohol consumption</strong> can lead to <strong>impaired ADH secretion </strong>or <strong>function</strong>, contributing to<strong> electrolyte imbalances</strong> and an<strong> increased risk of dehydration.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Considering these points,<strong> option D) All the above is correct, </strong>as each listed factor can be associated with<strong> chronic alcoholism</strong> and its <strong>impact on the body.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Options A, B, and C are</strong> individually <strong>correct </strong>but <strong>D </strong>encompasses <strong>all the possible findings, </strong>making it the most comprehensive choice.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"1\" style=\"list-style-type:lower-roman\">\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Increase </strong>in serum levels of <strong>gamma-glutamyl transferase (GGT) and alanine transaminase (ALT)</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Decrease</strong> in <strong>aldehyde dehydrogenase </strong>activity (in <strong>liver cells and RBCs</strong>) -<strong> best </strong>marker for<strong> alcohol abuse.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Disialotransferrin</strong> (<strong>sialic acid</strong> groups are removed from<strong> transferrin</strong>) level in blood- <strong>highly sensitive marker</strong> for <strong>chronic</strong> <strong>alcohol abuse.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Vasudevan 9/e: 140-141.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
