      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. C)&nbsp; Inhibition of dehydrogenase enzymes by NADH</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The<strong> large anion gap and hypoglycemia</strong> in a known <strong>alcoholic</strong> can be attributed to the <strong>metabolic effects of ethanol metabolism,</strong> particularly the <strong>inhibition</strong> of various<strong> dehydrogenase enzymes</strong> by the <strong>accumulation of NADH. Ethanol </strong>metabolism <strong>increases </strong>the <strong>NADH/NAD+ ratio </strong>in the <strong>liver,</strong> which <strong>inhibits</strong> key enzymes in<strong> gluconeogenesis </strong>(such as<strong> lactate dehydrogenase and malate</strong> <strong>dehydrogenase</strong>) and the <strong>TCA cycle.</strong> This <strong>inhibition </strong>leads to <strong>decreased glucose production </strong>and an accumulation of organic acids, contributing to<strong> both hypoglycemia</strong> and a <strong>high anion gap acidosis</strong>, respectively.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">&nbsp;<u>Explanation:</u></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A. Decreased secretion of glucagon:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> While glucagon secretion may be affected in <strong>chronic alcoholics</strong> due to <strong>pancreatic</strong> <strong>damage</strong>, it is <strong>not </strong>the primary cause of the<strong> large anion gap or hypoglycemia </strong>in <strong>acute ethanol intoxication.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B.&nbsp; Increased secretion of insulin:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>Acute ethanol ingestion</strong> typically <strong>does not</strong> cause an <strong>increase in insulin secretion.</strong> In fact, <strong>hypoglycemia</strong> in this context is <strong>more </strong>related to the <strong>inhibition of gluconeogenesis and glycogenolysis</strong> rather than insulin-mediated glucose uptake.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D. Inhibition of glycogenolysis by ethanol:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> While <strong>ethanol </strong>can <strong>impair glycogenolysis,</strong> the <strong>more </strong>significant impact on the <strong>anion gap and hypoglycaemia</strong> is through the <strong>inhibition of dehydrogenase enzymes</strong> by the<strong> increased NADH/NAD+ ratio, </strong>affecting <strong>gluconeogenesis </strong>and leading to the <strong>accumulation of organic acids.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Alcoholics do not</strong> frequently eat while<strong> binge drinking &rarr;</strong> so most likely his<strong> liver glycogen stores </strong>become<strong> depleted and</strong> <strong>cannot increase</strong> his <strong>blood glucose levels.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The <strong>metabolic stress</strong> in them leads to the<strong> increase in secretion of epinephrine</strong> and other <strong>hormones </strong>&rarr; <strong>mobilize fatty</strong> <strong>acids</strong> from <strong>stored triglycerides in adipose cells</strong> &rarr; undergo<strong> beta-oxidation </strong>&rarr; get converted to <strong>ketone bodies </strong>because of the <strong>inhibition of the TCA cycle </strong>by <strong>high levels of NADH</strong> (produced by the oxidation of ethanol first to acetaldehyde and acetate). </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Key<strong> gluconeogenic dehydrogenases</strong> are also <strong>inhibited by the elevated levels of NADH,</strong> including <strong>lactate dehydrogenase, glycerol 3-phosphate dehydrogenase, </strong>and <strong>malate dehydrogenase.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Vasudevan 9/e: 140-141.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
